{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646149"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:27:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:27:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18162"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18162"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.7,0.14,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10876"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66049"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7322"},{"type":"tags","id":"7378"},{"type":"tags","id":"7383"},{"type":"tags","id":"7384"},{"type":"tags","id":"7385"},{"type":"tags","id":"11414"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27557"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following rotator cuff muscles is most commonly torn due to its anatomical position?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infraspinatus","Supraspinatus","Subscapularis","Teres minor","Teres major"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraspinatus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is the most commonly torn rotator cuff muscle. It is located in a position where it is susceptible to impingement and wear, particularly as it passes beneath the acromion. This anatomical position places it in a zone of high risk for tears, especially in individuals who perform repetitive overhead activities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einfraspinatus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is less commonly torn compared to supraspinatus, although it can be involved in rotator cuff injuries, particularly in conjunction with supraspinatus tears.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubscapularis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is located on the anterior aspect of the scapula and is less commonly involved in isolated rotator cuff tears. It is more often affected in cases of anterior shoulder instability or trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eteres minor\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is the smallest of the rotator cuff muscles and is infrequently torn in isolation. It is more commonly involved in massive rotator cuff tears that affect multiple tendons.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eteres major\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the rotator cuff. It is a muscle of the upper arm that assists in adduction and medial rotation of the humerus, and it is not typically involved in rotator cuff injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The supraspinatus muscle is the most commonly torn rotator cuff muscle due to its anatomical position and function.","The supraspinatus tendon is particularly vulnerable to injury because it passes beneath the acromion, where it can be compressed or impinged.","Rotator cuff tears are a common cause of shoulder pain and dysfunction, often requiring clinical evaluation and imaging for diagnosis."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66049"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18162"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66049"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T16:16:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T16:16:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10876"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80750"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api